AUDIO: 'So, at this point there is no question that AI video is here and well, it\'s here to stay. Actually, I just clicked into a weather report and found an AI avatar hosting it. True [music] story. That\'s said, given that it\'s a weather report, I still only give it about a 30%'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'chance of being right. Point being that yes, AI video\'s moment is just beginning and to [music] that, I\'ve been seeing a recent uptick in the comments to the effect of like this all looks really cool, but I have no idea what you\'re'

[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'talking about. And look, that is fair. [music] On the channel, I generally talk about the bleeding edge of not only the technology, but the workflows we\'re utilizing. And so, a lot of information has compounded and compressed. So,'

[00:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; what I really wanted to do with today\'s video is make the too afraid to ask for dummies video that should bring everyone up to speed [music] and give some ideas on where things are headed. Now, for our power users that might be watching, I do'

[00:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'encourage you to stick around as obviously I can\'t cover everything here. So, do let me know what I missed and well, please help some newcomers out in the comments. [music] All right, with that let\'s dive in. So, briefly I did just kind of quickly'

[01:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'want to speed run the history of AI video since well, I mean if you haven\'t been keeping an eye on it, it it probably does seem like it popped up out of nowhere. So, if you weren\'t aware, the roots of all of this actually go all the way back to 2015 with Google\'s'

[01:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'DeepDream. These were super trippy and psychedelic videos that were quickly dubbed puppy slug videos. To note, this is not video generation. This is the neural network hallucinating over'

[01:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'existing video. If you\'ve ever wondered why so many dogs, it\'s actually the folder that DeepDream was trained on. 10% of the images were dogs, so it became obsessed with dogs. I get it. The next big breakthrough came in 2017 with'

[01:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Transformers, which we generally think of as like the technology that gave birth to things like ChatGPT. Transformers were originally introduced and I\'m not going to make a Robots in Disguise joke here as attention'

[01:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mechanisms. Basically, the ability for a model to understand the relationship across long sequences. As it turns out, that\'s pretty helpful for generating video. And finally, in 2022 came the introduction of Stable Diffusion and'

[02:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'well, I mean modern diffusion models. This was the thing that allowed for an AI model to generate a burst of static and then begin hallucinating over that static with whatever you prompted. Whenever you see seed written in any'

[02:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generator, what that seed is the initial burst of static. So, if you change that, chances are you\'re going to change your image. And most recently was the introduction of world models, but we are kind of getting a bit ahead of ourselves'

[02:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here. We\'ll circle back to this much later on. So, if you\'re just getting started with creative AI tools, there are you know, kind of two paths to explore here. One is by utilizing open source tools in order to generate video,'

[02:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'audio, images essentially locally on your own machine. The other is by utilizing closed source models on platforms. These are the ones that you have definitely heard of like Sora, for example. Now, to be honest, most'

[02:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'high-level video creators kind of do a hybrid of local and platform. That\'s said, for this video we are going to be focusing on the platform side. That said, if you are interested in local generation, do make sure that you are'

[03:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'subscribed as like hopefully next weekish I should have a big tutorial on that coming up. Moving on to some techniques, the bread and butter of AI video comes down to one of four things really. There\'s text to video, image to'

[03:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'video, video to video and most recently introduced reference or like ingredients to video. Now, with text to video as the name implies, we write a prompt and the model will attempt to generate what we'

[03:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ask of it. This often results in more stable outputs considering that you know, the model knows what it knows, so it can take your prompt and interpret it as such. With image to video, we are providing the model with an image that'

[03:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it is treating as a first frame and then telling it like start here and then follow my prompt directions from there. In general, at this point the image to video route is usually the preferred'

[04:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'method as it means you can lock the aesthetic look of your video. Again, by telling the model, hey, this is what everything looks like. For video to video, well, I mean this almost kind of harkens back to the old puppy slug days'

[04:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because essentially we are providing video to the model along with an image or a text prompt and saying like hallucinate this over the video that I provided to you. And finally, a fairly'

[04:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'recent addition to our workflows is reference or ingredients to video. They all call it something different, but essentially it\'s the idea of being able to give the model like, hey, here\'s an image of a person, a place and a thing'

[04:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and then having the video model generate a video from that. So, it is sort of a hybrid between image and text prompting. Yeah, it can be very powerful. We\'ll talk more about the various video models in a bit, but for now let\'s focus in on'

[04:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'images. Now, when it comes to image generators, there are a ton of them out there. And and just to simplify, I\'d say that the leading models are Midjourney, which I know that some are going to'

[05:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'disagree with, but you know, I think it\'s great if you\'re just getting started and still has some of the best like artsy aesthetics around. That said, it does lack repeatability and controllability.'

[05:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Another image model that is pretty commonly used is Flux from Black Forest Labs who just released a version two. This one is good for like really photographic results. I will say that'

[05:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'version two is was very early in right now. So, it can be a little bit on the wonky side. I do expect to see that improve quite a bit over the next few months. SeaArt Dream from ByteDance is'

[05:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'also pretty good, definitely worth checking out. And like I said, a whole host of others, but undoubtedly the current king of the hill is from Big Daddy G. You have probably heard of it.'

[05:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It is called Nano Banana. Now, the big thing with Nano Banana and specifically the Nano Banana Pro version that was like fairly recently released is that it not only works as an image generator, but it also works as an image editor and'

[06:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you can prompt for some pretty complex changes. It\'s also very good at taking references and being able to create new images with those references. I did a whole video on Nano Banana Pro when it'

[06:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'launched and actually has a pretty cool interview with one of the team members. It\'s linked down below if you want the full run-through, but the important takeaway here is that Nano Banana Pro was a major breakthrough in terms of'

[06:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'consistency across image edits. So, it\'s a fairly common workflow these days to generate an image and then expand or edit that image in Nano Banana Pro, which essentially end up creating'

[06:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'storyboards that act as your first frames for your video projects. Now, where do you find Nano Banana Pro? Well, I mean it is kind of all over the place. If you\'re very new to all of this and you want to check it out, the easiest'

[06:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'way is just pop on Google\'s Gemini and ask it to generate or edit an image. Yeah, that\'s Nano Banana Pro at work right there. So, if you want to unleash the full power of Nano Banana Pro, the easiest way to do so is to start'

[07:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'exploring it on some of the platforms. Now, before we head over there and onto the video side, I do just want to quickly stop down for a moment to talk about prompting. So, at one point in time there was like an entire cottage'

[07:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'industry that was devoted to selling you tutorials on how to prompt. I\'m not going to necessarily discount that because in the earliest days of Stable Diffusion, I mean the prompts looked like this. That said, at this point I am'

[07:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here to tell you that there is no right or wrong way to prompt. While yes, there are some techniques that you can utilize which we\'ll go over in just a second, for the most part I mean you can pretty much direct conversationally and most'

[07:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'image and video models, I mean they understand what you\'re saying. And I don\'t know if this is a big secret or not, but most of us are using a large language model like ChatGPT or Gemini or even Claude to help develop our'

[08:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'prompts. So, we\'ll speak conversationally to the LLM and have it spit out a prompt and then run that prompt over to an image or video generator. Because I will say that having that second layer of a language'

[08:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'model going through and rewriting your prompt does help the video or image model really shine. That said, I always do recommend and encourage you to look through the prompt that was provided to you and make changes. Don\'t let the'

[08:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'machine do all the work. There also is a technique called JSON prompting. This is JavaScript Object Notation. Essentially, it\'s you know, asking the LLM to develop a prompt and then when it delivers it,'

[08:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it will do so in this format with the idea being that the image or video model will be able to parse the information quicker and more reliably. Some people swear by the JSON prompt technique,'

[09:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'others outright dismiss it. The best I can say, give it a shot, see if it clicks for you. All you have to do is simply ask an LLM, please provide this to me in JSON format and yeah, I mean it knows what to do. Prompting out of the'

[09:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'way, let\'s slide over to the video side of things. But first, a word from today\'s sponsor. So, this is a segment I think you\'re going to find pretty interesting. If you\'re like me, you\'ve always written off voice to text because well, I mean it never works the way we'

[09:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'want it to. So, when WhisperFlow who are sponsoring today\'s video reached out, to be honest, I was a bit on the fence, but then a few people I trust were like, no, seriously, you should try it. And well, here we are, so clearly I liked it. So,'

[09:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'first off, I mean why use voice to text at all? Well, for one, there there actually is a real cognitive difference between writing a thought and verbalizing a thought. One isn\'t necessarily better than the other, they'

[09:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'just engage different parts of the brain. And that can be very useful when you\'re stuck staring at a blank document or testing, it is faster and more accurate. With Flow, you can actually stay in, well, the flow. Just talk uninterrupted and capture your full'

[10:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'thoughts. But before we get to use cases, there are just like two quick things I wanted to point out. First, as mentioned, it is really accurate. It\'ll handle something like the JSON prompt configuration, "In my CSS is breaking'

[10:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the layout on my HTML page." Solidly done. It can also auto format numbered lists. For example, "How are we going to make a bazillion dollars?" Well, three easy steps. Number one, steal underwear.'

[10:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Number two, {question mark}. Number three, profit. Don\'t you go stealing my business plan. And here\'s a cool thing that it can do. It can course correct your natural speech. For example, I\'m thinking about downgrading my ChatGPT'

[10:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'subscription. No, wait, my Claude subscription. So yeah, it totally understood that that no wait was me changing my mind. Second, you do not need a fancy mic. It is called Whisper Flow for a reason. In fact, living up to'

[10:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'its name, you can just whisper and Whisper Flow will pick it up. Um okay, I\'m about to get loud again, but I do want to point out &gt;&gt; no matter what mic you\'re using, it\'s it\'s going to work just fine. Now, a few ways that I\'ve been using it a lot,'

[11:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'aside from email responses, or sending quick Slack messages, which I actually really do like because it does preserve your voice. For example, "Hey, I\'m sending you a quick Slack DM using Whisper Flow. So, this part may end up'

[11:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in the video. Just a quick FYI." We\'ll see if we get a response back on that. To be honest, anybody that\'s in a Slack with me is pretty used to getting weird messages like that. Well, I mean, at the end of the day, let\'s be honest, most'

[11:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'messages and emails are kind of quick hit responses anyway. So, this is the perfect use case. But since we do so much image and video work on the channel, one really useful feature is snippets. Basically, it\'s like a verbal'

[11:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'macro. So, here we are over on Google\'s Flow platform. So, I\'ve actually created a snippet, so I can just simply say "Cinematic prompt." And that expands out to include prompt details that I want to'

[11:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'include. But one of my favorite use cases lately is, well, over the holidays, I picked up a remarkable tablet, one of the basic e-ink with like the intention of doing daily journaling. That has not gone great. So, instead, I\'ve been using Flow to just kind of'

[12:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'brain dump for 5 or 10 minutes while I\'m having my coffee in the morning. And that has captured way more information. And no, I\'m not going to show you all of my neuroses. That\'s for ChatGPT to diagnose. But listen, don\'t take my word'

[12:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for it. You can try Whisper Flow for free for 14 days. And if you sign up with my link down below, you get an extra month of Pro for free. Yeah, as it turns out, speech to text has gotten really good. Now, similar to the image'

[12:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'side of things, when it comes to video generation, well, there are a ton of options to choose from. As a quick sidebar, I am not going over AI avatars in this video. But if you are interested'

[12:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in that aspect, there is a recent video that I did going over them. That is linked down below. Now, with the video generators, each of them have things that they are very good at. Well, to be honest, they all have things that they are not very good at. The trick is just'

[13:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to figure out where that overlaps. All of the models have a, well, to be honest, a fairly similar feature set as well. That said, as a sidebar on features, anytime that we see any one of these models make a version number jump,'

[13:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'so like version two to version three, what you will see is that a lot of those old features will break, and then over the course of that next version, slowly be re-introduced back in. Broadly speaking, the reason that this happens'

[13:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is anytime that a model makes a number jump, the architecture usually changes, which breaks, you know, the feature set. It\'s just kind of I mean, you just kind of got to get used to it. It\'s it\'s always two steps forward, one step back. All that said, currently, I would say'

[13:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that the top-ranking video models are Google\'s VO3.1, which not only provides us with really great video outputs, but will also generate sound and dialogue for us. I\'m really excited to be back'

[13:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for VO3.1. I was worried that everyone forgot about me, but now I\'m back. Also, Kling 2.6, which actually did just recently introduce sound as well. Now,'

[14:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that said, that sound can be pretty wonky right now, but I do think that Kling 2.6 is one of the best models for motion and movement. Possibly a controversial take, but I\'m also going'

[14:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to say OpenAI\'s Sora 2. This is a really good video model that probably does provide the best audio out of all of them, but it\'s also hamstrung by the fact that you can\'t generate an image to'

[14:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'video with what it decides is realistic-looking people. I do want to shout out the very recently released Runway Gen 4.5 image to video, which I just did a whole video on'

[14:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'yesterday. Through my tests, it\'s looking pretty good. Although, to note at this time, there is no audio on this one. Some other models that I do want to mention, Luma Labs Ray 3, which is always a contender, but in particular,'

[14:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this one is very good with its video to video features. Video to video is a technique that I think is very underutilized. It is something that I want to focus more on in 2026, mostly because it\'s like the technique'

[15:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that provides you with the most amount of control. Another model that I wanted to shout out is ByteDance\'s SeaDance, which does provide you with audio as well. It\'s just incredibly infuriating to me that ByteDance named their image'

[15:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'model SeaDream and their video model SeaDance, because I get the two of them screwed up all the time. So yeah, that\'s kind of just scratching the surface. It should give you enough to chew on and then explore from there. Now, people are always asking me like, "What is the best'

[15:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'video model?" And I\'m going to be totally honest here, there isn\'t one. Like there is no one tool for every job. And ultimately, since I don\'t know what your end goal is, the only way for you to find out is to experiment to find out'

[15:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what works and what doesn\'t work. Now, luckily, these days we don\'t have to subscribe to 50 different services to get the chance to try them out, because most models are available via an API, or application protocol interface, which'

[16:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'means that, you know, other platforms can utilize them on their platforms. And again, offhand, I would say that the most popular and commonly used ones are Freepik, who I\'ve I looked at like a while ago. I haven\'t I should probably'

[16:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'circle back at some point or another. But I will say that Freepik is like has most major models on there. And I\'ve I always noticed that they are very quick to adapt and adopt new models as they pop up. Higgsfield, who actually seem to'

[16:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have carved out a pretty unique position where as new techniques and workflows emerge with things like Nano Banana or other models, they are very quick to create easy-to-use graphic UIs for those'

